    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/18a69f667744642c1c749945278e01c7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2352386,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2060915,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2060915/naveenkumar1410",
                "reputation": 1613,
                "display_name": "NaveenKumar1410",
                "accept_rate": 67
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1362997306,
            "creation_date": 1362994137,
            "body": "<p>Check PrintStream.java file to know the process of <strong>print<\/strong> method.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://luckytoilet.wordpress.com/2010/05/21/how-system-out-println-really-works/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Check here for detailed flow of process<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15335051,
            "question_id": 15334933,
            "last_edit_date": 1362997306
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/04a1df195427f6aa88140d5860c274e3?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2314635,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2031946,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2031946/uba",
                "reputation": 2031,
                "display_name": "uba"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1362994236,
            "creation_date": 1362994236,
            "body": "<p><code>out<\/code> is a static member of class <code>System<\/code> having type <code>PrintStream<\/code> <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/lang/System.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/lang/System.html<\/a>. You can create <code>PrintStream<\/code> objects for files and use them similarly. <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/io/PrintStream.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/io/PrintStream.html<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15335081,
            "question_id": 15334933
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "user_type": "does_not_exist",
                "display_name": "user2030471"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1362994540,
            "creation_date": 1362994120,
            "body": "<p>Different implementations of Java may have different ways of doing the thing in question. You can check out their source if you're interested in how it's being done.<\/p>\n\n<p>For example in <code>HotSpot<\/code> VM, <code>out<\/code> is a <code>java.io.PrintStream<\/code> reference which internally uses a <code>java.io.BufferedWriter<\/code> to write to the standard output.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15335046,
            "question_id": 15334933,
            "last_edit_date": 1362994540
        }
    ],
